{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}} {{Use British English|date=November 2017}} The '''Records of the Parliaments of Scotland to 1707''' is an online publication of the [[Scottish Parliament]] and the [[University of St Andrews]] arising from a project to create a comprehensive [[on-line database]] of the proceedings of the [[Parliament of Scotland]] from 1235 to the [[Act of Union (1707)|Act of Union]]. The website was launched in 2008.
The project was formulated by Professor [[Keith Brown (professor)|Keith Brown]] of [[St Andrews University]] in 1996. Funding was quickly approved by then-[[Secretary of State for Scotland]] [[Michael Forsyth, Baron Forsyth of Drumlean|Michael Forsyth]] and announced by then-[[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[John Major]] on 4 July 1996. As well as the initial funding by the [[Scottish Office]], monies for what became the Scottish Parliament Project were provided by the [[Scottish Government]], the [[Arts and Humanities Research Board]], and the [[Strathmartine Trust]].
Under the general editorship of Professor Brown, the eleven-year project to complete the database created a work of around fifteen million words in size. It includes parallel translations from the original [[Latin]], [[French language|Norman French]], and [[Scots language|Scots]].
The primary editors of the text of each period were: * [[Alastair Mann]] (Early Modern) * [[Gillian McIntosh]] (Early Modern) * [[Pamela Ritchie]] (Early Modern) * [[Roland Tanner (historian)|Roland Tanner]] (Medieval and Latin)
The lead website developer was [[Swithun Crowe]].
==See also== *[[National Archives of Scotland]] *[[Advocates' Library]]
