[[File:The Social hall alcatraz.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The ruined Social Hall of Alcatraz]]
[[File:Alcatraz aerial.jpg|thumb|right|The Social Hall is located on the left of the picture, beyond the white tower]]
The '''Social Hall''', also known as the '''Officers' Club''', was a social club located on the northwestern side of the island of [[Alcatraz]], off the coast of [[San Francisco]], USA. Located in close proximity to the [[Power House (Alcatraz)|Power House]], [[Alcatraz Water Tower|water tower]] and [[Former Military Chapel (Bachelor Quarters)]], it formerly housed the post exchange.<ref name="DickinsonBlair2010">{{cite book|last1=Dickinson|first1=Greg|last2=Blair|first2=Carole|last3=Ott|first3=Brian L.|title=Places of Public Memory: The Rhetoric of Museums and Memorials|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BN5IV8RZ2jQC&pg=PA187|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=2 August 2010|publisher=University of Alabama Press|isbn=978-0-8173-5613-2|page=187}}</ref> The club was a social venue for the Federal Penitentiary workers and their families on the island to unwind after a hard week's work dealing with America's most hardened criminals after they'd been locked up at 17:30.<ref name="Barter1999">{{cite book|last=Barter|first=James|title=Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MIYBYBk6UEsC|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=September 1999|publisher=Lucent Books|isbn=978-1-56006-596-8|page=83}}</ref><ref name="Jr2011"/> It was burned down by a fire of disputed origins during the [[Occupation of Alcatraz]] in 1970; leaving a shell which still remains.
==Facilities and organization== [[File:Alcatraz Island 03.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The Social Hall building can be seen between the water tower and the powerhouse on the right]] The club had a small bar, library, large dining and dance floor, billiards table, ping pong table and a two-lane bowling alley, and was the centre of social life on the island for the employees of the penitentiary.<ref name="Albright2008"/><ref name="StaffMorgan2010">{{cite book|author1=BMI Staff|author2=Tina Dittbenner Morgan|title=Al Capone Does My Shirts Study Guide and Student Workbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ki2dVEzAgX0C&pg=PA66|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=1 September 2010|publisher=BMI Educational Services|isbn=978-1-60933-701-8|page=66}}</ref><ref name="Dunbar1999">{{cite book|last=Dunbar|first=Richard|title=Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OoXM5O9glN8C&pg=PA48|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Casa Editrice Bonechi|isbn=978-88-8029-940-0|page=48}}</ref> It regularly hosted dinners, bingo events, and from the 1940s onwards showed movies every Sunday night after they had been shown to the inmates during the day on Saturday and Sunday.<ref name="Albright2008"/><ref name="Alcatraz">{{cite book|title=Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ivs4jv5KCQC&pg=PT128|accessdate=31 August 2012|publisher=Chronicle Books|isbn=978-1-4521-1310-4|page=128}}</ref> The employees formed bowling leagues and held championships<ref name="Jr2011">{{cite book|last=Jr|first=Jerry Lewis Champion|title=The Fading Voices of Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GxH3-mB5rCcC&pg=PA96|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=27 January 2011|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4567-1488-8|page=96}}</ref> Food was supplied from leftovers in the kitchen and often brought by the attendees so it was usually free for the guests of the parties held here.<ref name="Gregory2008">{{cite book|last=Gregory|first=George H.|title=Alcatraz Screw: My Years as a Guard in America's Most Notorious Prison|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WIEUx4IGqHMC&pg=PA189|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=28 April 2008|publisher=University of Missouri Press|isbn=978-0-8262-1396-9|page=189}}</ref><ref name="Albright2008"/>
The club was responsible for organizing numerous special events on the island (held either in the hall or the [[Parade Grounds]]) and the fundraising associated with it, anything from ice cream and watermelon feasts to [[Halloween]] fancy dress and Christmas parties.<ref name="Albright2008">{{cite book|last=Albright|first=Jim|title=Last Guard Out: A Riveting Account by the Last Guard to Leave Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fmVGYLGkLl4C&pg=PA192|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=30 March 2008|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4343-5077-0|page=192}}</ref><ref name="Wellman2008">{{cite book|last=Wellman|first=Gregory L.|title=A History of Alcatraz Island:: 1853-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1duAUPaHSgcC&pg=PA110|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=28 May 2008|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-5815-8|page=110}}</ref>
